            "last_activity_date": 1502353292,
            "creation_date": 1502353292,
            "body": "<p>Yeah, that's standard practice followed to separate environment dependent properties and have them injected using spring.profile.active, but the scenario you described seems more to be human error and can occur with any utility, one can have test to verify properties but it introduces maintainability issue. I prefer to manage production related properties using spring cloud config (<a href=\"https://cloud.spring.io/spring-cloud-config/\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">here<\/a>) because production properties may contain db credentials and secret keys which may get leaked. <\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 45608190,
            "question_id": 45607915
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9e83287ab6cd3218e6f1168b5f146cf9?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 7727204,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 5851464,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/5851464/phanindra-gopishetty",
                "reputation": 169,
                "display_name": "Phanindra Gopishetty"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1502353583,
            "creation_date": 1502353583,
            "body": "<p>You can use a default properties file. If there is no property in a particular env specific file then it will look into this properties file.<\/p>\n\n<p>wherever possible while resolving property in spring try providing default value.\nFor eg.\n@Value(\"${mongodb.url:127.0.0.1}\")<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 45608281,
            "question_id": 45607915
        }
